Date:  0/0/1869
Source:  TrNZi
Author:
Vol / Page:  1/iii/9
Edition:
Quote:  Probably to the genus Zosterops ... belongs a small migratory bird, called by the natives `Kanohi-mowhiti'. it is properly a South island species ... it crossed over [to the North island], for the first time in the memory of the native inhabitants, in the winter of 1856.
Notes:  (Buller Ornithology)

Date:  0/0/1888
Source:  Birds of New Zealand
Author:  BULLER
Vol / Page:  1/77
Edition:
Quote:  ZOSTEROPS CAERULESCENS. (THE SiLVER-EYE.) ... Native names. Tau-hou, Whiorangi, Hiraka, Motingitingi, Kanohi-mowhiti, Karu-patene, Karu-ringi, Karu-hiriwha, Poporohe, and iringatau. <i>ibid.</i> 81
Notes:  The natives distinguish the bird as Tau-hou ..., or Kanohi-mowhiti (which may be interpreted as spectacle-eye or ring-eye). it is also called Poporoke and iringatu, names suggested by its accidental or periodical occurrence.
